In the prefix-sum + hashmap approach, the map stores the remainder as the key and the number of times that remainder has
occurred so far as the value. When we do count += map.get(remainder), we are adding the current value stored for that 
remainder to the total count, because each previous occurrence of the same remainder forms a valid subarray with the 
current sum. Then, when we update the map with map.put(remainder, map.getOrDefault(remainder, 0) + 1), the getOrDefault 
reads the existing value if the key is already present, or uses 0 if the key isn’t in the map yet. We then add 1 to count 
this current prefix sum and write it back. So, the default value is only used if the key doesn’t exist, otherwise it’s ignored, 
and the existing value is incremented by 1. This ensures that the map always
correctly tracks the number of times each remainder has appeared, whether it’s a new remainder or one we’ve seen before.
